Events in world sport through the years 1771 to 1775.

==[[Boxing]]==
'''Events'''
* 18 May 1771 — British champion Bill Darts defeated by the Irishman Peter Corcoran at [[Epsom Downs Racecourse]] after seven minutes of the first round. Darts was later accused of accepting a bribe from Captain O'Kelly, a famous turfman, to lose the fight and was obliged to retire in disgrace from boxing.<ref name=Darts>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/darts-william.htm |title=Bill Darts |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=PC>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/corcoran.htm |title=Peter Corcoran |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>
* 1772 — [[Benjamin Brain|"Big Ben" Brain]] defeated Jack Clayton at [[Kingswood, South Gloucestershire|Kingswood]], the round and length of the fight are unknown.<ref name=BB>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/brain-benjamin.htm |title=Ben Brain |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref> 
* 1773 — Harry Sellers won against minor opponents in many numerous fights until 1775, whereabouts unknown.<ref name=HS>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/sellers-harry.htm |title=Harry Sellers |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref> 
* June 1774 — Corcoran is believed to have successfully defended the title on a number of occasions during the early 1770s but the only opponent who had any credibility was Sam Peters in June 1774 at [[Waltham Abbey (town)|Waltham Abbey]]. Corcoran won the fight in fifteen minutes after three rounds.<ref name=PC/>
* 1774 — "Big Ben" Brain defeated Bob Harris at Kingswood, the round and length of the fight are both unknown.<ref name=BB/>

==[[Cricket]]==
'''Events'''
* 1771 — the [[Nottingham Cricket Club|Nottingham]] v [[Sheffield Cricket Club|Sheffield]] match is the first known mention of cricket in [[Nottinghamshire]], even though the Nottingham club was already well-established.{{fact|date=July 2017}}
* 1771 — the [[Chertsey Cricket Club|Chertsey]] v [[Hambledon Club|Hambledon]] match at [[Laleham Burway]] was enlivened by a furious dispute when [[Thomas White (cricketer, born c. 1740)|Thomas "Daddy" White]] used an extra wide bat to completely obscure his wicket. The Hambledon players objected and a formal protest was written by bowler [[Thomas Brett (cricketer)|Thomas Brett]] and signed by himself, [[Richard Nyren]] and [[John Small (cricketer)|John Small]]. It brought about a change in the ''[[Laws of Cricket]]'', as confirmed in 1774, whereby the maximum width of the bat is set at four and one quarter inches (the Law is extant).{{fact|date=July 2017}}
* 1772 — detailed scorecards became commonplace and this marked the beginning of "[[first-class cricket]]" as a ''statistical'' concept.{{fact|date=July 2017}}
* 1773 — a [[grandstand]] was erected on two occasions at [[Bourne Paddock]], possibly the first time these structures are known to have been used.{{fact|date=July 2017}}
* 1774 — the ''[[Laws of Cricket]]'' were revised by a committee meeting at the ''Star and Garter'' on [[Pall Mall, London|Pall Mall]] in London. This version of the Laws includes [[leg before wicket]] (lbw) and the maximum width of the bat.{{fact|date=July 2017}}
* May 1775 — demands for a third [[stump (cricket)|stump]] were voiced after a [[single wicket cricket|single wicket]] match at the [[Artillery Ground]] in which [[Lumpy Stevens]] beat [[John Small (cricketer)|John Small]] at least three times only for the ball to pass through the [[wicket]], still made of two uprights and a crosspiece, without disturbing it. Although the petition was granted soon afterwards, research has discovered that the introduction of the third stump in practice was gradual and the two-stump wicket continued for a number of years yet.{{fact|date=July 2017}}
* 13 July 1775 — [[John Small (cricketer)|John Small]] scored 136 [[not out]] for [[Hampshire county cricket teams|Hampshire]] ''versus'' [[Surrey county cricket teams|Surrey]] at [[Broadhalfpenny Down]], the earliest definite [[century (cricket)|century]] in [[first-class cricket]].<ref>Haygarth, p. 25.</ref>

